### ============================================================
### CIRCULAR DEPENDENCY TEST
###
### Scenario:
###   A (id=1) is parent of B (id=11)
###   A (id=1) is parent of C (id=12)
###   C (id=12) is parent of D (id=17)
###
###   Step 1: Move A (id=1) under B (id=11)
###           => Creates cycle: B -> A -> B
###
###   Step 2: Move A (id=1) under D (id=17)
###           => Creates deeper cycle: D -> C -> A -> D
###
### Expected: Should throw an error (IllegalArgumentException or similar)
### Current behavior: moveCategory only checks direct self-reference
###                   (newParentId.equals(id)), so cycles ARE NOT detected!
### ============================================================

### Step 1 - Direct cycle: make A (Electronics) a child of B (Smartphones)
### Electronics (1) is currently the parent of Smartphones (11)
### This creates: Smartphones -> Electronics -> Smartphones
PATCH http://localhost:8080/api/categories/admin/1/move?newParentId=11
Accept: application/json

###

### Step 2 - Deeper cycle: make A (Electronics, id=1) a child of D (iPhone Cases, id=17)
### Chain: iPhone Cases -> Smartphones -> Electronics -> iPhone Cases
PATCH http://localhost:8080/api/categories/admin/1/move?newParentId=17
Accept: application/json

###

### Step 3 - Self-reference: move category to itself (this IS caught)
### Expected: IllegalArgumentException - "Category cannot be its own parent"
PATCH http://localhost:8080/api/categories/admin/1/move?newParentId=1
Accept: application/json
